📘 Project Overview and Scenario
This Digital Literacy project is designed to develop awareness and practical understanding of responsible and 
safe use of digital technologies among students. The project is based on the scenario of a student acting as a 
“Digital Ambassador,” whose role is to guide peers in navigating the digital world effectively and securely.
Through a series of structured tasks, the project covers important aspects of digital literacy, including online safety, 
phishing and UPI fraud awareness, responsible social media usage, digital communication etiquette, and the use of modern
tools such as Google Forms, Canva, GitHub, and HackerRank. Each task focuses on building both theoretical knowledge and 
practical skills, such as creating quizzes, designing infographics, writing professional emails, and analysing real-world cybercrime cases.
The overall objective of this project is to equip students with essential digital skills, promote safe online behavior,
and prepare them for academic, professional, and everyday digital interactions in an increasingly technology-driven world.



Over the past few days, I have worked with two key platforms—Google Forms and HackerRank—to build practical tools and 
strengthen my technical skills.
Using Google Forms, I designed a Digital Literacy Awareness Quiz for my batchmates. The quiz includes five questions
covering important topics such as phishing, strong password practices, secure website identification, misinformation 
verification, and two-factor authentication. I enabled quiz mode, assigned point values, and created answer keys for
accurate evaluation. This experience helped me understand how to design structured digital assessments, which can be useful for 
academic purposes like conducting surveys, collecting feedback, and creating interactive quizzes for projects and research.
On HackerRank, I practised Python programming with a focus on NumPy operations. I solved problems involving array creation using 
functions such as zeros, ones, eye, and identity to generate matrices of specific dimensions. These exercises enhanced my understanding 
of numerical computing, which is important for fields like data analysis, machine learning, and engineering.
Overall, working with these platforms has equipped me with valuable practical skills—Google Forms for assessment design and 
HackerRank for coding proficiency—both of which will support my academic work and future career in technology.

